SECTION 4 - CONTRACTING FOR SERVICE
Section 4.1 Availability
Interruptible transportation service shall be available to any qualified applicant upon submission of a properly completed application form, payment of all required fees as set forth herein, and execution of a written agreement between Shipper and Transporter. All applications for transportation must be made using the Interruptible Transportation Request Form included herein. Transporter is not required to provide any requested transportation service for which capacity is not available, or which would require the construction or acquisition of any new facilities unless Shipper shall first deposit with Transporter the estimated cost of such facilities, including income tax gross-up and applicable operation and maintenance. Transporter shall refund to Shipper any excess of estimated cost over actual cost. As an alternative, Transporter and Shipper may agree to a reimbursement schedule based upon a contracted rate and term.
Shipper and Transporter shall execute duplicate originals of a written agreement for service under this Operating Statement. Items covered in the Transportation Service Agreement shall include, but not be limited to, transportation rate(s), the maximum daily transportation quantity, agreement term, renewal provisions (if any), effective date, and addresses for notice purposes. Such agreement shall be deemed to include all other provisions of this Operating Statement. Before transportation commences, all other required transportation agreements (such as those for interstate pipeline transportation) shall be executed with copies provided to Transporter.
Section 4.2 Creditworthiness
A. Transporter shall not commence service or continue service to Shipper if Shipper fails to meet the creditworthiness criteria outlined in this Section.
B. Acceptable creditworthiness is demonstrated by meeting the following criteria: 1. At Transporter's request, Shipper shall provide current financial statements, annual reports, 10-K reports or other filings with regulatory agencies which discuss the Shipper's financial status, a list of all corporate affiliates, parent companies and subsidiaries, and any reports from credit reporting and bond rating agencies which are available. Transporter shall apply consistent evaluative practices to determine the acceptability of Shipper's overall financial condition, working capital, and profitability trends. 2. At Transporter's request, Shipper shall provide a bank reference and at least two trade references. The results of reference checks and any credit reports submitted under B.1 of this Section must show that Shipper's obligations are being paid on a reasonably prompt basis. 3. Shipper must not be operating under any chapter of the bankruptcy laws and must not be subject to liquidation or debt reduction procedures under state laws such as an assignment for the benefit of creditors, or any informal creditors' committee agreement. An exception can be made for a Shipper who is a debtor in possession operating under Chapter XI of the Federal Bankruptcy Act, but only with adequate assurance that Transporter's billing under the Transportation Service Agreement will be paid promptly as a cost of administration under the federal court's jurisdiction. 4. Shipper should not be subject to the uncertainty of pending liquidation or regulatory proceedings in state or federal courts which could cause a substantial deterioration in its financial condition, which could cause a condition of insolvency, or the ability to exist as an ongoing business entity. 5. No significant collection lawsuits or judgments are outstanding which would seriously reflect upon Shipper's ability to remain solvent. 6. If any of the events or actions described in subsections B.3, B.4, or B.5 or this Section are initiated or imposed during the terms of service under the Transportation Service Agreement, Shipper shall provide notification thereof to Transporter within two (2) working days of any such initiated or imposed event or action. 7. If Shipper has an ongoing business relationship with Transporter, no delinquent balances should be consistently outstanding for billings made previously by Transporter and Shipper must have paid its account in the past according to the established terms and not made deductions or withheld payment for claims not authorized by contract. 8. A new credit appraisal shall not be conducted when an existing Transportation Service Agreement is amended or a request for a new Transportation Service Agreement is made unless Shipper's payment history with Transporter has not been satisfactory or there is a bona fide basis for questioning Shipper's creditworthiness.
C. If Shipper fails to demonstrate creditworthiness either prior to receiving service or after service has commenced under the Transportation Service Agreement, Transporter may require Shipper: 1. To make a payment in advance equal to the total charges estimated to be incurred by Shipper based on the volumes specified in the Transportation Service Agreement for a period of two (2) months; or 2. To provide a standby irrevocable letter of credit drawn upon a bank acceptable to Transporter; or 3. To provide a guarantee by a person or another entity which satisfies the credit appraisal; or 4. To provide such other security as is mutually acceptable to both Transporter and Shipper.

SECTION 5 - RECEIPTS AND DELIVERIES; MEASUREMENT
Section 5.1 Receipt and Delivery Obligations
Transporter shall receive and deliver gas to Shipper at points located on Transporter's distribution system as shown on the executed Transportation Service Agreement.
Transporter has no obligation on any day to deliver quantities of gas greater than receipts (net of fuel retention) for a Shipper's account, nor to accept quantities of gas (net of fuel retention) for Shipper's account greater than deliveries accepted by the Shipper.
Section 5.2 Measurement Unit
Unless otherwise agreed in writing, all transported volumes will be measured on a dekatherm (Dt) basis.
Section 5.3 Measurement of Deliveries
Transportation delivery points requested by Shipper may be equipped with monthly gas measurement equipment instead of daily gas measurement equipment. If daily measurement does not exist at any transportation delivery point requested by Shipper, and Shipper elects to equip such points with daily measurement and/or Transporter requires Shipper to equip such points with daily measurement, the Transporter shall have no obligation to provide transportation service to that point unless and until Shipper agrees to the execute a Telemetering Agreement with Transporter. Transporter will then install, at Shipper's expense, a daily measurement device which will provide information concerning the pressure, temperature and amount of natural gas being delivered to Shipper's facilities. Transporter will be responsible for the normal installation and maintenance of the equipment including all necessary gas piping. Shipper's obligation for payment shall commence on the date of the installation of the equipment. Shipper shall either pay Transporter for the cost and installation within thirty (30) days of the date installation is complete or in twelve (12) equal monthly installments with interest at the rate of one percent (1%) per month. Transporter shall at all times retain all right, title and interest to the equipment. Shipper will be responsible for ensuring that electric and telecommunication services are available at the meter site in accordance with Transporter's specifications. Copies of current specifications are available from Transporter's Engineering Section.

SECTION 10 - GAS QUALITY
Section 10.1 Determination of Btu Content
All gas received by Transporter will be delivered to the Point(s) of Delivery on a dekatherm-equivalent basis. In order to provide for dekatherm-equivalent deliveries, Transporter may attribute Btu content to deliveries by either:
A. testing by the gravity balance method at such times as meters are tested in compliance with the rules and regulations of the PSCWV, as the same may be amended from time to time;
B. using reference points on the inlet pipeline (either upstream or downstream of the Shipper's meter connection);
C. utilizing the system-wide average Btu content of gas delivered by Transporter; or
D. such other method as mutually agreed upon by Transporter and Shipper.
Section 10.2 Delivery Pressures
All quantities of gas delivered by Transporter to the Point(s) of Delivery shall be made at the pressures existing in Transporter's pipeline facilities from time to time. All quantities of gas delivered by Shipper to Transporter to the Point(s) of Receipt shall be made at the pressures existing in Transporter's pipeline facilities. Shipper shall install pressure protection equipment at the request of Transporter.
Section 10.3 Gas Quality Standards
All gas received by Transporter from Shipper shall conform to the more restrictive of, (1) the gas quality standards specified in this Operating Statement (which are intended to reflect the currently effective rules and regulations of the PSCWV); and, (2) the tariff of any interstate pipeline to which gas is delivered directly from Transporter's system for Shipper's account. The gas quality standards referenced in the first clause of the preceding sentence are the following: gas delivered to Transporter at the Point(s) of Receipt by Shipper
A. shall not contain an amount of water vapor exceeding seven (7) pounds per million cubic feet of gas, or an amount of water vapor exceeding the quantity that is required for saturation of the gas at the flowing temperature and pressure of the gas; provided, however, no gas shall contain any water in the liquid state;
B. shall be free from air, sulphur in any form or compound (other than when inserted as an odorant), nitrogen (no greater than three (3) mole %), carbon dioxide (no greater than three (3) mole %), total inerts (no greater than five (5) mole %), and other deleterious substances which may adversely affect its use as a fuel or use for other purposes, or be injurious to equipment and machinery.

SECTION 11 - POSSESSION, TITLE, INDEMNIFICATION
Section 11.1 Possession of and Title to Gas
As between Transporter and Shipper, Shipper shall be deemed to be in control and possession of the gas prior to receipt by Transporter and after delivery to Shipper or for the account of Shipper. Transporter shall be deemed to be in control and possession of the gas to be transported upon receipt of such gas at the Point(s) of Receipt until it shall have been delivered to Shipper or for the account of Shipper at the Point(s) of Delivery. Title to all gas transported shall at all times rest with Shipper.
Section 11.2 Indemnification
Shipper shall indemnify Transporter and save it harmless from all suits, judgments, claims, actions, debts, liabilities, levies, accounts, damages, costs, losses, and expenses arising from or out of adverse claims of any or all persons to said gas, including but not limited to claims, suits, actions, and demands which may arise due to the nonpayment of landowner royalties, overriding royalties, or rentals thereon or therefrom. Provided, however, Shipper shall not indemnify Transporter for any liability to the extent that such liability arises out of Transporter's intentional misconduct or negligence.

SECTION 12 - MISCELLANEOUS
Section 12.1 Notices
Except as herein otherwise provided, any request, demand, or statement provided for in Shipper's Transportation Service Agreement, or any notice which either party may desire to give to the other, shall be in writing and shall be considered as duly delivered when mailed by registered or certified mail to the Post Office address of the receiving party(ies). Routine communications, including monthly statements, shall be considered as duly delivered when mailed by ordinary mail, by electronic devices, or by facsimile.
Section 12.2 Lawful Obligations
Except as otherwise stated herein, any article or provision declared or rendered unlawful by a court of law or regulatory agency with jurisdiction over the parties or deemed unlawful because of a statutory change will not otherwise affect the lawful obligations that arise under the Shipper's Transportation Service Agreement.
Section 12.3 Waivers
No waiver by either party of one or more defaults by the other in the performance of any provisions of this Operating Statement or Shipper's Transportation Service Agreement shall operate or be construed as a waiver of any other default or defaults, whether of a like or of a different character.
Section 12.4 Successors
Any company which shall succeed by purchase, merger, or consolidation of the properties, substantially as an entirety, of Transporter or Shipper, as the case may be, shall be entitled to the rights and shall be subject to the obligations of its predecessor in title under this Operating Statement and Shipper's Transportation Service Agreement.
Section 12.5 Assignment
No assignment of Shipper's Transportation Service Agreement or any of the rights or obligations thereunder shall be made unless there first shall have been obtained the consent thereto in writing of the other party. Such consent shall not be unreasonably withheld.
Section 12.6 Interpretation
The subject headings of the articles of this Operating Statement are inserted for the purpose of convenient reference and are not intended to be a part of the Transportation Service Agreement nor considered in any interpretation of the same. Whenever the context requires it, the singular shall include the plural, and vice versa.

SECTION 9 - BILLING AND PAYMENT
Section 9.1 Payment of Bill
Transporter shall render a bill to Shipper on or about the tenth (10th) day of each month for the services rendered by Transporter during the previous month, along with all other charges billable under Shipper's Transportation Service Agreement. Shipper shall render payment in full to Transporter on or before the last day of each month ("Due Date").
Section 9.2 Interest
Should Shipper fail to tender full payment by the Due Date, interest per annum on the unpaid portion of the bill shall accrue at the rate of one percent (1%) per month on outstanding balances which exceed $500 from the Due Date until the date payment is received.
Section 9.3 Termination for Nonpayment
If such failure to pay continues for thirty (30) days after the Due Date, Transporter, in addition to any other remedy it may have, may suspend further transportation of gas to Shipper until such amount is paid.
Section 9.4 Disputed Bills
If Shipper in good faith disputes the amount of any bill or any part thereof, and shall pay to Transporter such amount as it concedes to be correct, and at any time thereafter within thirty (30) days of a demand made by Transporter, shall furnish good and sufficient surety bond, guaranteeing payment to Transporter of the amount ultimately found to be due under such bill after a final determination, which may be reached either by agreement between the parties or judgment of a court, then Transporter shall not be entitled to suspend further transportation of gas unless and until default be made in the conditions of such bond.
Section 9.5 Error Adjustments
In the event an error is discovered in the amount billed in any statement rendered by Transporter, such error shall be adjusted within thirty (30) days of the determination thereof; provided that claim therefor shall have been made within sixty (60) days from the date of discovery of such error, but in any event within twelve (12) months from the date such statement is rendered.
Section 9.6 Security Deposit
Transporter may at any time require Shipper to post a security deposit. Such deposit shall not exceed two (2) months' (estimated) average bills.

SECTION 8 - TRANSPORTATION SCHEDULING ORDERS
Shippers are subject to Transporter's issuance of transportation scheduling orders ("TSOs"), due to operational or financial impacts on Transporter's system, which will direct Shippers to adjust their nominations to match anticipated requirements. Failure to comply with a TSO may result in Transporter, at its discretion and in accordance with reasonable and standard industry practice, adjusting Shipper's nomination. Failure to comply with a TSO will result in the billing of the following incremental charges:
A. The payment of a gas cost equal to the Reference Price as defined in Section 6.2.1 above entitled "Purchase from Shipper" or Section 6.2.2 above entitled "Sale to Shipper", whichever is applicable, times the TSO difference which is defined as the imbalance between Shipper's nomination and daily usage, as calculated by Transporter on those days subject to the TSO; and,
B. The payment of any charges or costs incurred by Transporter due to Shipper's failure to comply with a TSO. Where such charges or costs are incurred by Transporter due to more than one Shipper's failure to comply with a TSO, Transporter's request for payment will be assessed to those Shippers on a pro-rata basis.
Additionally, on any day when Shipper has been given timely notice by Transporter that a TSO has been issued and is in effect, any quantity of gas consumed by Shipper in excess of Shipper's nomination may be subject to a penalty not to exceed $15.00 per Dt on such excessive volumes.
Shippers in compliance with a TSO shall not be subject to any incremental charges or costs.

SECTION 7 - FORCE MAJEURE CURTAILMENT
Section 7.1 Force Majeure
Transporter may discontinue or curtail deliveries of gas at any time if required in its judgment by weather or the unplanned necessity for repairs, operating changes, or other Force Majeure as hereinafter defined, upon such notice as is reasonable under the circumstances. The term "Force Majeure" as used herein shall mean acts of God, strikes or other industrial disturbances, lockouts or other labor disturbances, acts of the public enemy, wars, blockades, insurrections, riots, epidemics, landslides, lightning, earthquakes, fires, storms, floods, washouts, arrests and restraints by governments and people, civil disturbances, explosions, breakage of or accidents to machinery or lines of pipe, the unplanned necessity for making repairs to or the alteration of machinery or lines of pipe, freezing of wells or lines of pipe, partial or entire failure of such wells and any other causes, whether of the kind enumerated herein or otherwise, not within the control of the party having the difficulty.
Section 7.2 Suspension of Obligations
In the event either party is rendered unable, wholly or in part, by Force Majeure (as defined in the section above entitled "Force Majeure") to carry out its obligations other than the obligation to make payments of amounts accrued and due at the time thereof, it is agreed that on such party's giving notice and full particulars of such Force Majeure in writing, by electronic delivery, or by facsimile to the other party as soon as reasonably practicable after the occurrence of the cause relied on, the obligations of both parties, so far as they are affected by such Force Majeure, shall be suspended during the continuance of any inability so caused.

SECTION 2 - INTRODUCTION; CHARACTER OF SERVICE; AUTHORIZATIONS
Section 2.1 Introduction
Hope Gas, Inc. ("Transporter"), a West Virginia corporation with its principal place of business in Morgantown, West Virginia, is engaged in the business of purchasing and distributing natural gas in the State of West Virginia. It serves residential, commercial, wholesale, and industrial customers in at least 35 of West Virginia's 55 counties via more than 3,000 miles of pipeline within West Virginia. Transporter's operations are subject to the jurisdiction of the Public Service Commission of West Virginia ( "PSCWV"), and it has been declared exempt from the provisions of the Natural Gas Act ("NGA") and regulation by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("FERC") pursuant to NGA Section 1(c) (the Hinshaw Amendment). Hope Gas, Inc., 30 FERC ? 62,081 (1985). Transporter has interconnections with three interstate natural gas pipelines.
Transporter has also acquired gathering pipelines exempt from FERC jurisdiction, some of which provide service to Transporter's customers under its PSCWV tariff. The services and rates for service on such facilities are subject to full regulation by the PSCWV under Hope's PSCWV tariff.
On March 27, 2012, in Docket No. CP12-27, Transporter received a blanket certificate of limited jurisdiction from FERC, pursuant to 18 C.F.R. ? 284.224, to engage in certain transportation of natural gas for third parties ("Shipper" or "Shippers") through its own facilities to interconnections with interstate pipelines for further transportation and consumption of such gas outside the State of West Virginia. Hope Gas, Inc., 138 FERC ? 62,304. ("Blanket Certificate"). The Blanket Certificate authorized Transporter to provide transportation service to the same extent, and pursuant to the same regulatory terms, as interstate transportation service provided by intrastate pipelines under Section 311(a)(2) of the Natural Gas Policy Act of 1978. Hope filed its baseline Statement of Operating Conditions on April 26, 2012, in Docket No. PR12-23. Pursuant to applicable FERC regulations, Transporter is using, for transportation services provided hereunder, the transportation rates and fuel retention charges approved by the PSCWV for comparable in-state services.
Transportation service under Transporter's Blanket Certificate shall be undertaken only to the extent such service is "on behalf of" an interstate pipeline company or a local distribution company ("LDC") served by an interstate pipeline company. To be considered "on behalf of" the specified entities, there must be an interstate pipeline or an LDC (other than Transporter) that either (1) has physical custody of and transports the natural gas at some point, or (2) holds title to the natural gas at some point, which may occur prior to, during, or after the time that the gas is being transported by the Company, for a purpose related to its status and functions as an interstate pipeline or LDC, as applicable. All Shippers receiving service hereunder shall warrant that they satisfy the foregoing "on behalf of" requirement. Transporter may also periodically cause gas to be delivered into its gathering pipelines on its own behalf to enable Transporter to satisfy its gas utility obligations to provide adequate gas supply and pressure on those pipelines to maintain gas service to its customers served under its PSCWV tariff. See e.g., Equitrans, L.P., 181 FERC ? 61,235 (2022).
It is the policy of Transporter to provide interruptible transportation service for any eligible Shipper only under a written transportation service agreement ("Transportation Service Agreement") containing the terms and conditions generally acceptable to Transporter and in accordance with those additional terms and conditions set forth herein, executed after consideration of its existing commitments, pipeline design capacity, available pipeline capacity, points of receipt and delivery, and other factors deemed material by Transporter and applied on a not unduly discriminatory basis.
This Statement of Operating Conditions ("Operating Statement") is filed to comply with 18 C.F.R. Section 284.123(e) and may be modified, subject to applicable approvals, from time to time as Transporter may deem necessary and appropriate.
Section 2.2 Character of Service
The service to be provided under this Operating Statement shall be interruptible. Transporter reserves the right to refuse to begin service, or to discontinue any service, where, in Transporter's discretion, (1) the service would impair its primary public service obligation pursuant to regulation by the PSCWV, or (2) the service would require or result in any change to Transporter's jurisdictional or regulatory status. Transporter has no standing obligation to provide service hereunder other than interruptible service which is at all times subordinate to any and all firm services provided by Transporter as part of its natural gas distribution operations.
The character of the interruptible transportation service rendered shall be the same as that which Shipper has contracted for in its Transportation Service Agreement with Transporter. All interruptible service is conditioned upon the availability of capacity and/or supplies sufficient to provide such service without detriment or disadvantage to Shippers who are dependent upon Transporter's general system supply and capacity.
Transporter shall not provide firm transportation service under this Operating Statement.
Section 2.3 Authorizations
Transporter's transactions entered into hereunder are based on the good faith understanding that all acts, obligations, and services performed or to be performed by Transporter hereunder, and the charges therefore, are exempt from the regulation of FERC or any successor federal governmental authority except as provided by Section 284.224 of FERC's regulations. Transporter reserves the right to terminate immediately any service hereunder if, in Transporter's discretion, any governmental act occurs which would require Transporter to offer or furnish service hereunder other than those contemplated in Transporter's executed Transportation Service Agreements or which would cause any impairment in Transporter's ability to render any service, require Transporter to offer additional service, or require a change in Transporter's jurisdictional or regulatory status.
Transporter shall file to update this Operating Statement to reflect any new rate changes or surcharges that FERC, the PSCWV, or any other applicable regulatory agency or governmental body requires Transporter either to bear or to collect from Shipper.

SECTION 3 - STATEMENT OF RATES
The rates for interruptible transportation service under this Operating Statement shall be agreed between Transporter and Shipper and shall be between the maximum and minimum rates as set forth below:
A. Commodity Charge: There shall be a charge for all gas delivered to Shipper during the billing month as follows:
Maximum Charge: $2.548 per Dt 1/ Minimum Charge: $0.000 per Dt
1/ Includes a Pipeline Replacement and Expansion Program ("PREP") charge of $1.016.
B. Fuel Retention Charge: All transportation quantities received from Shipper shall be subject to a fuel retention charge. Unless otherwise agreed in writing, Transporter shall retain 5.5% of gas delivered by Shipper for transportation pursuant to this Operating Statement.
Transporter may agree with Shipper to discount these maximum volumetric rates on a not unduly discriminatory basis; provided, however, that in no event shall such discounted rates recover less than Transporter's Fuel Retention Charge.

SECTION 6 - BALANCING
Section 6.1 Balancing at Delivery Points with Daily Gas Measurement
A. Nominations and Upstream Imbalances. The Shipper is responsible for making advance nominations to Transporter for the quantity of gas to be received for Shipper's account each day. All such nominations must be submitted electronically and by the deadlines established by Transporter and are subject to acceptance by Transporter. Shipper shall endeavor to insure that the daily quantity of gas received by Transporter for Shipper's account, net of fuel retention, matches the daily quantity of gas accepted by Shipper at its facilities. All imbalances on upstream pipelines are Shipper's responsibility.
B. Daily Imbalance. Daily imbalances between receipts for a Shipper's account, net of fuel retention, and deliveries to the Shipper are subject to an imbalance charge. Shippers shall pay a daily balancing charge of $0.158 per Dt on their actual daily imbalances.
Section 6.2 Balancing at Delivery Points without Daily Gas Measurement
Shippers with transportation delivery points not equipped with daily gas measurement equipment are subject to Monthly Imbalance Service at those delivery points.
Monthly Imbalances. Imbalances between total monthly supplies received by the Transporter for Shipper's account, net of fuel retention, and total monthly deliveries to Shipper shall be resolved at the end of each month as follows. These charges are in addition to all other transportation charges.
1. Purchase from Shipper. In any month where deliveries to a Shipper are less than receipts by Transporter or Shipper's account, net of fuel retention, Transporter shall purchase the imbalance gas from Shipper at a price which shall be calculated as follows:
a. Reference Price Determination. The Reference Price each month for imbalances resolved by Transporter purchasing gas from the Shipper shall consist of a Base Commodity Rate and a Transportation Component less, during the months of April and October, fifty cents ($0.50 per Dt). The Base Commodity Rate shall equal the lowest of the daily postings during the month gas was delivered for Appalachia, Dominion South Point, Absolute Low, as published in Gas Daily (The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.). The Transportation Component shall be equal to the interruptible transportation rate plus fuel retention of Dominion Energy Transmission, Inc., or a successor company.
b. Reference Price Multiplier. The Reference Price shall be adjusted as provided in the following table:
Deliveries More than Percentage of Receipts Net of Fuel Reference Price
2% 100% 4% 90% 6% 80% 8% 70% 10% 60% 12% 50%
2. Sale to Shipper. In any month where deliveries to a Shipper are greater than receipts for Shipper's account, net of fuel retention, Transporter shall sell the imbalance to Shipper at a price which shall be calculated as follows:
a. Reference Price Determination. The Reference Price for imbalances resolved by Transporter selling gas to Shipper shall be the Maximum Reference Price multiplied by the Reference Price Multiplier (both as defined below).
b. Maximum Reference Price. The Maximum Reference Price for each month shall consist of a Base Commodity Rate and a Transportation Component, plus during the months of April and October, an additional fifty cents ($0.50 per Dt). The Base Commodity Rate shall equal the highest of the daily postings during the month gas was delivered for Appalachia, Dominion South Point, Absolute High, as published in Gas Daily (The McGraw-Hill Companies, Inc.). The Transportation Component shall be equal to the interruptible transportation rate plus fuel retention of Dominion Energy Transmission, Inc., or a successor company.
c. Reference Price Multiplier. The Reference Price shall be adjusted as provided in the following table:
Receipts Net of Fuel Percentage of More than Deliveries Reference Price
2% 100% 4% 110% 6% 120% 8% 130% 10% 140% 12% 150%
3. Should Gas Daily change the name of the column heading or postings listed thereunder, it will be recognized as a name change only and not a location change. If Gas Daily ceases to publish its daily absolute high and low prices for Dominion South Point, Transporter will choose a comparable substitute.
4. To the extent that a Reference Price is derived from the published Tariff Record of an interstate pipeline, the Tariff Record used to determine the applicable rates shall be those available the first day of the month following the month when service was rendered. Even if a new Tariff Record subsequently becomes effective retroactively, no adjustment shall be made. Should the name of the rate or service change, it will be a name change only and not a rate change. Should a particular tariff service be eliminated, Transporter will choose a comparable substitute.
Section 6.3 Restrictions on Gas Usage
A Shipper receiving transportation service is expected to match its usage with the level of supplies being received by Transporter for its account. Upon such notice as is reasonable under the circumstances (orally or in writing, including electronically or via facsimile), to any Shipper that it needs to restrict its gas usage, the Shipper must curtail its usage as requested by Transporter. Any Shipper failing to voluntarily reduce its usage will be subject to the applicable overrun provisions as defined in Section 6.4 below entitled "Overrun Charges" and/or possibly to having its service forcibly curtailed or interrupted.
Section 6.4 Overrun Charges
Whenever Transporter notifies Shipper that it needs to restrict its gas usage as provided in Section 6.3 above entitled "Restrictions on Gas Usage" and it fails to do so, Shipper shall be subject to a pro rata share of any overrun charges billed to Transporter by upstream pipelines. All of these charges are in addition to those otherwise billable under this Operating Statement or Transportation Service Agreement.
